[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning is an interdisciplinary area of machine learning and optimal control that has, as main objective, finding an approximately optimal policy for MDPs where transition probabilities and rewards are unknown.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning can solve Markov-Decision processes without explicit specification of the transition probabilities which are instead needed to perform policy iteration.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] In this setting, transition probabilities and rewards must be learned from experience, i.e. by letting an agent interact with the MDP for a given number of steps.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] While this function is also unknown, experience during learning is based on $(s,a)$ pairs (together with the outcome $s'$ ; that is, "I was in state s and I tried doing a and $s'$ happened").
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Thus, one has an array Q and uses experience to update it directly.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Another application of MDP process in machine learning theory is called learning automata.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] This is also one type of reinforcement learning if the environment is stochastic.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] The first detail **learning automata** paper is surveyed by Narendra and Thathachar (1974), which were originally described explicitly as finite-state automata.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Similar to reinforcement learning, a learning automata algorithm also has the advantage of solving the problem when probability or rewards are unknown.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] The difference between learning automata and Q-learning is that the former technique omits the memory of Q-values, but updates the action probability directly to find the learning result.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Learning automata is a learning scheme with a rigorous proof of convergence.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] The states of such an automaton correspond to the states of a "discrete-state discrete-parameter Markov process".
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] At each time step *t* = 0,1,2,3,..., the automaton reads an input from its environment, updates P(*t*) to P(*t* + 1) by *A*, randomly chooses a successor state according to the probabilities P(*t* + 1) and outputs the corresponding action.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] The automaton's environment, in turn, reads the action and sends the next input to the automaton.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Other than the rewards, a Markov decision process $(S,A,P)$ can be understood in terms of Category theory.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Namely, let ${\mathcal {A}}$ denote the free monoid with generating set *A*.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Let **Dist** denote the Kleisli category of the Giry monad.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] Then a functor ${\mathcal {A}}\to \mathbf {Dist}$ encodes both the set *S* of states and the probability function *P*.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] In this way, Markov decision processes could be generalized from monoids (categories with one object) to arbitrary categories.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] One can call the result $({\mathcal {C}},F:{\mathcal {C}}\to \mathbf {Dist} )$ a *context-dependent Markov decision process*, because moving from one object to another in ${\mathcal {C}}$ changes the set of available actions and the set of possible states.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] The terminology and notation for MDPs are not entirely settled.
[src:ppo-algorithm/markov-decision-process] In addition, the notation for the transition probability varies.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] In policy-based RL, the actor is a parameterized policy function $\pi _{\theta }$ , where $\theta$ are the parameters of the actor.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The actor takes as argument the state of the environment s and produces a probability distribution $\pi _{\theta }(\cdot \mid s)$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] If the action space is discrete, then $\sum _{a}\pi _{\theta }(a\mid s)=1$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] If the action space is continuous, then $\int _{a}\pi _{\theta }(a\mid s)\mathrm {d} a=1$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The **policy gradient** is defined as $\nabla _{\theta }J(\theta )$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Different policy gradient methods stochastically estimate the policy gradient in different ways.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The goal of any policy gradient method is to iteratively maximize $J(\theta )$ by gradient ascent.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Since the key part of any policy gradient method is the stochastic estimation of the policy gradient, they are also studied under the title of "Monte Carlo gradient estimation".
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The **REINFORCE algorithm**, introduced by Ronald J.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Williams in 1992, was the first policy gradient method.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] By the tower law and the previous lemma.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The score function $\nabla _{\theta }\ln \pi _{\theta }(A_{t}\mid S_{t})$ can be interpreted as the direction in the parameter space that increases the probability of taking action $A_{t}$ in state $S_{t}$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Here, $\alpha _{i}$ is the learning rate at update step i .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] REINFORCE is an **on-policy** algorithm, meaning that the trajectories used for the update must be sampled from the current policy $\pi _{\theta }$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This can lead to high variance in the updates, as the returns $R(\tau )$ can vary significantly between trajectories.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Many variants of REINFORCE have been introduced, under the title of **variance reduction**.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This can be proven by applying the previous lemma.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] If ${\textstyle b_{i}}$ is chosen well, such that ${\textstyle b_{i}(S_{t})\approx \sum _{\tau =t}^{T}(\gamma ^{\tau }R_{\tau })=\gamma ^{t}V^{\pi _{\theta _{i}}}(S_{t})}$ , this could significantly decrease variance in the gradient estimation.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] One common approach is to train a separate function that estimates the value function, and use that as the baseline.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This is one of the actor-critic methods, where the policy function is the actor and the value function is the critic.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Some more possible ${\textstyle \Psi _{t}}$ are as follows, with very similar proofs.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The natural policy gradient method is a variant of the policy gradient method, proposed by Sham Kakade in 2001.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Unlike standard policy gradient methods, which depend on the choice of parameters $\theta$ (making updates coordinate-dependent), the natural policy gradient aims to provide a coordinate-free update, which is geometrically "natural".
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Inverting $F(\theta )$ is computationally intensive, especially for high-dimensional parameters (e.g., neural networks).
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Practical implementations often use approximations.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The natural gradient descent is theoretically optimal, *if* the objective is truly a quadratic function, but this is only an approximation.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] TRPO's line search and KL constraint attempts to restrict the solution to within a "trust region" in which this approximation does not break down.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This makes TRPO more robust in practice.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Note that in general, other surrogate advantages are possible: $L(\theta ,\theta _{i})=\mathbb {E} _{s,a\sim \pi _{\theta _{i}}}\left[{\frac {\pi _{\theta }(a|s)}{\pi _{\theta _{i}}(a|s)}}\Psi ^{\pi _{\theta _{i}}}(s,a)\right]$ where $\Psi$ is any linear sum of the previously mentioned type.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Indeed, OpenAI recommended using the Generalized Advantage Estimate, instead of the plain advantage $A^{\pi _{\theta }}$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The surrogate advantage $L(\theta ,\theta _{t})$ is designed to align with the policy gradient $\nabla _{\theta }J(\theta )$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Thus it is a "surrogate" of the real objective.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This reduces the problem to a quadratic optimization, yielding the natural policy gradient update: $\theta _{i+1}=\theta _{i}+{\sqrt {\frac {2\epsilon }{g^{T}F^{-1}g}}}F^{-1}g.$ So far, this is essentially the same as natural gradient method.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] A further improvement is proximal policy optimization (PPO), which avoids even computing $F(\theta )$ and $F(\theta )^{-1}$ via a first-order approximation using clipped probability ratios.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] In words, gradient-ascending the new surrogate advantage function means that, at some state $s,a$ , if the advantage is positive: $A^{\pi _{\theta _{t}}}(s,a)>0$ , then the gradient should direct $\theta$ towards the direction that increases the probability of performing action a under the state s .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] However, as soon as $\theta$ has changed so much that $\pi _{\theta }(a|s)\geq (1+\epsilon )\pi _{\theta _{t}}(a|s)$ , then the gradient should stop pointing it in that direction.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Thus, PPO avoids pushing the parameter update too hard, and avoids changing the policy too much.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] To be more precise, to update $\theta _{t}$ to $\theta _{t+1}$ requires multiple update steps on the same batch of data.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] It would initialize $\theta =\theta _{t}$ , then repeatedly apply gradient descent (such as the Adam optimizer) to update $\theta$ until the surrogate advantage has stabilized.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] It would then assign $\theta _{t+1}$ to $\theta$ , and do it again.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] During this inner-loop, the first update to $\theta$ would not hit the $1-\epsilon ,1+\epsilon$ bounds, but as $\theta$ is updated further and further away from $\theta _{t}$ , it eventually starts hitting the bounds.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] For each such bound hit, the corresponding gradient becomes zero, and thus PPO avoid updating $\theta$ too far away from $\theta _{t}$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This is important, because the surrogate loss assumes that the state-action pair $s,a$ is sampled from what the agent would see if the agent runs the policy $\pi _{\theta _{t}}$ , but policy gradient should be on-policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] So, as $\theta$ changes, the surrogate loss becomes more and more *off*-policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This is why keeping $\theta$ *proximal* to $\theta _{t}$ is necessary.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This has been used in training reasoning language models with reinforcement learning from human feedback.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] The Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) is a minor variant of PPO that omits the value function estimator V .
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] That is, it is the standard score of the rewards.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] As before, the KL penalty term can be applied to encourage the trained policy to stay close to a reference policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] GRPO was first proposed in the context of training reasoning language models by researchers at DeepSeek.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] Methods like TRPO, PPO and natural policy gradient share a common idea - while the policy should be updated in the direction of the policy gradient, the update should be done in a safe and stable manner, typically measured by some distance with respect to the policy before the update.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] A similar notion of update stability is found in proximal convex optimization techniques like Mirror Descent.
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] This leads to reconsidering the policy update procedure as an optimization procedure aimed at finding an optimal policy, in the (non-convex) optimization landscape of the underlying Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:ppo-algorithm/policy-gradient-method] In fact, the KL divergence penalty also appears in the original PPO paper, suggesting the MDPO perspective as a theoretical unification of the main derivation concepts behind many concurrent policy gradient techniques.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The predecessor to PPO, Trust Region Policy Optimization (TRPO), was published in 2015.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] It addressed the instability issue of another algorithm, the Deep Q-Network (DQN), by using the trust region method to limit the KL divergence between the old and new policies.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] However, TRPO uses the Hessian matrix (a matrix of second derivatives) to enforce the trust region, but the Hessian is inefficient for large-scale problems.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] It was essentially an approximation of TRPO that does not require computing the Hessian.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The KL divergence constraint was approximated by simply clipping the policy gradient.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Since 2018, PPO was the default RL algorithm at OpenAI.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] PPO has been applied to many areas, such as controlling a robotic arm, beating professional players at Dota 2 (OpenAI Five), and playing Atari games.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] TRPO, the predecessor of PPO, is an on-policy algorithm.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] It can be used for environments with either discrete or continuous action spaces.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Like all policy gradient methods, PPO is used for training an RL agent whose actions are determined by a differentiable policy function by gradient ascent.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Intuitively, a policy gradient method takes small policy update steps, so the agent can reach higher and higher rewards in expectation.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Policy gradient methods may be unstable: A step size that is too big may direct the policy in a suboptimal direction, thus having little possibility of recovery; a step size that is too small lowers the overall efficiency.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] To solve the instability, PPO implements a *clip function* that constrains the policy update of an agent from being too large, so that larger step sizes may be used without negatively affecting the gradient ascent process.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] To begin the PPO training process, the agent is set in an environment to perform actions based on its current input.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] In the early phase of training, the agent can freely explore solutions and keep track of the result.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Later, with a certain amount of transition samples and policy updates, the agent will select an action to take by randomly sampling from the probability distribution $P(A|S)$ generated by the policy network.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The actions that are most likely to be beneficial will have the highest probability of being selected from the random sample.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] After an agent arrives at a different scenario (a new state) by acting, it is rewarded with a positive reward or a negative reward.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The objective of an agent is to maximize the cumulative reward signal across sequences of states, known as *episodes*.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The *advantage function* (denoted as A ) is central to PPO, as it tries to answer the question of whether a specific action of the agent is better or worse than some other possible action in a given state.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] By definition, the advantage function is an estimate of the relative value for a selected action.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] If the output of this function is positive, it means that the action in question is better than the average return, so the possibilities of selecting that specific action will increase.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The opposite is true for a negative advantage output.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The advantage function can be defined as $A=Q-V$ , where Q is the discounted sum of rewards (the total weighted reward for the completion of an episode) and V is the baseline estimate.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Since the advantage function is calculated after the completion of an episode, the program records the outcome of the episode.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Therefore, calculating advantage is essentially an unsupervised learning problem.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The baseline estimate comes from the value function that outputs the *expected* discounted sum of an episode starting from the current state.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] In the PPO algorithm, the baseline estimate will be noisy (with some variance), as it also uses a neural network, like the policy function itself.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] With Q and V computed, the advantage function is calculated by subtracting the baseline estimate from the actual discounted return.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] If $A>0$ , the actual return of the action is better than the expected return from experience; if $A<0$ , the actual return is worse.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] In PPO, the *ratio function* ( $r_{t}$ ) calculates the probability of selecting action a in state s given the current policy network, divided by the previous probability under the old policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Hence, this ratio function can easily estimate the divergence between old and current policies.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The objective function of PPO takes the expectation operator (denoted as E ) which means that this function will be computed over quantities of trajectories.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] 2. $\operatorname {clip} (r_{t}(\theta ))\cdot A$ : the policy ratio is first clipped to the range $[1-\epsilon ,1+\epsilon ]$ ; generally, $\epsilon$ is defined to be 0.2.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Then, as before, it is multiplied by the advantage.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The fundamental intuition behind PPO is the same as that of TRPO: conservatism.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Clipping results in a conservative advantage estimate of the new policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The reasoning is that if an agent makes significant changes due to high advantage estimates, its policy update will be large and unstable, and may diverge from the optimal policy with little possibility of recovery.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] There are two common applications of the clipping function: when an action under a new policy happens to be a good choice based on the advantage function, the clipping function limits how much credit can be given to a new policy for up-weighted good actions.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] On the other hand, when an action under the old policy is judged to be bad, the clipping function constrains how much the agent can accept the down-weighted bad actions of the new policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Consequently, the clipping mechanism is designed to discourage the incentive of moving beyond the defined range by clipping both directions.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The advantage of this method is that it can be optimized directly with gradient descent, as opposed to the strict KL divergence constraint of TRPO, making the implementation faster and more intuitive.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] After computing the clipped surrogate objective function, the agent has two probability ratios: one non-clipped and one clipped.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Then, by taking the minimum of the two objectives, the final objective becomes a lower bound (a *pessimistic* bound) of what the agent knows is possible.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] In other words, the minimum method makes sure that the agent is doing the safest possible update.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] PPO approximates what TRPO does, with considerably less computation.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] It uses first-order optimization (the clip function) to constrain the policy update, while TRPO uses KL divergence constraints (second-order optimization).
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Compared to TRPO, the PPO method is relatively easy to implement and requires less computational resource and time.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Therefore, it is cheaper and more efficient to use PPO in large-scale problems.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] While other RL algorithms require hyperparameter tuning, PPO comparatively does not require as much (0.2 for epsilon can be used in most cases).
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Also, PPO does not require sophisticated optimization techniques.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] It can be easily practiced with standard deep learning frameworks and generalized to a broad range of tasks.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Sample efficiency indicates whether the algorithms need more or less data to train a good policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] PPO achieved sample efficiency because of its use of surrogate objectives.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] The surrogate objective allows PPO to avoid the new policy moving too far from the old policy; the clip function regularizes the policy update and reuses training data.
[src:ppo-algorithm/proximal-policy-optimization] Sample efficiency is especially useful for complicated and high-dimensional tasks, where data collection and computation can be costly.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In machine learning, **reinforcement learning from human feedback** (**RLHF**) is a technique to align an intelligent agent with human preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It involves training a reward model to represent preferences, which can then be used to train other models through reinforcement learning.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In classical reinforcement learning, an intelligent agent's goal is to learn a function that guides its behavior, called a policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The function is iteratively optimized to increase the reward signal derived from the agent's task performance.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] However, explicitly defining a reward function that accurately approximates human preferences is challenging.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Therefore, RLHF seeks to train a "reward model" directly from human feedback.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The reward model is first trained in a supervised manner to predict if a response to a given prompt is good (high reward) or bad (low reward) based on ranking data collected from human annotators.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This model then serves as a reward function to improve an agent's policy through an optimization algorithm like proximal policy optimization.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF has applications in various domains in machine learning, including natural language processing tasks such as text summarization and conversational agents, computer vision tasks like text-to-image models, and the development of video game bots.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] While RLHF is an effective method of training models to act better in accordance with human preferences, it also faces challenges due to the way the human preference data is collected.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Though RLHF does not require massive amounts of data to improve performance, sourcing high-quality preference data is still an expensive process.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Furthermore, if the data is not carefully collected from a representative sample, the resulting model may exhibit unwanted biases.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Optimizing a model based on human feedback is desirable when a task is difficult to specify yet easy to judge.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, one may want to train a model to generate safe text that is both helpful and harmless (such as lacking bias, toxicity, or otherwise harmful content).
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Asking humans to manually create examples of harmless and harmful text would be difficult and time-consuming.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] However, humans are adept at swiftly assessing and comparing the harmfulness of different AI-generated text.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Therefore, a more practical objective would be to allow the model to use this type of human feedback to improve its text generation.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Despite the clear benefits of incorporating human feedback in training models, prior efforts—including some that leverage reinforcement learning (RL)—have encountered significant challenges.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Most attempts were either narrow and difficult to generalize, breaking down on more complex tasks, or they faced difficulties learning from sparse (lacking specific information and relating to large amounts of text at a time) or noisy (inconsistently rewarding similar outputs) reward functions.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF was not the first successful method of using human feedback for reinforcement learning, but it is one of the most widely used.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The foundation for RLHF was introduced as an attempt to create a general algorithm for learning from a practical amount of human feedback.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The algorithm as used today was introduced by OpenAI in a paper on enhancing text continuation or summarization based on human feedback, and it began to gain popularity when the same method was reused in their paper on InstructGPT.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF has also been shown to improve the robustness of RL agents and their capacity for exploration, which results in an optimization process more adept at handling uncertainty and efficiently exploring its environment in search of the highest reward.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Human feedback is commonly collected by prompting humans to rank instances of the agent's behavior.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] These rankings can then be used to score outputs, for example, using the Elo rating system, which is an algorithm for calculating the relative skill levels of players in a game based only on the outcome of each game.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] While ranking outputs is the most widely adopted form of feedback, recent research has explored other forms, such as numerical feedback, natural language feedback, and prompting for direct edits to the model's output.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] One initial motivation of RLHF was that it requires relatively small amounts of comparison data to be effective.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It has been shown that a small amount of data can lead to comparable results to a larger amount.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In addition, increasing the amount of data tends to be less effective than proportionally increasing the size of the reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Nevertheless, a larger and more diverse amount of data can be crucial for tasks where it is important to avoid bias from a partially representative group of annotators.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This implies that, under certain conditions, if a model is trained to decide which choices people would prefer between pairs (or groups) of choices, it will necessarily improve at predicting future preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This improvement is expected as long as the comparisons it learns from are based on a consistent and simple rule.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In the offline data collection model, when the objective is policy training, a pessimistic MLE that incorporates a lower confidence bound as the reward estimate is most effective.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Moreover, when applicable, it has been shown that considering K-wise comparisons directly is asymptotically more efficient than converting them into pairwise comparisons for prediction purposes.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A key challenge in RLHF when learning from pairwise (or dueling) comparisons is associated with the non-Markovian nature of its optimal policies.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Unlike simpler scenarios where the optimal strategy does not require memory of past actions, in RLHF, the best course of action often depends on previous events and decisions, making the strategy inherently memory-dependent.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF has been applied to various domains of natural language processing (NLP), such as conversational agents, text summarization, and natural language understanding.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Ordinary reinforcement learning, in which agents learn from their actions based on a predefined "reward function", is difficult to apply to NLP tasks because the rewards tend to be difficult to define or measure, especially when dealing with complex tasks that involve human values or preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF can steer NLP models, in particular language models, to provide answers that align with human preferences with regard to such tasks by capturing their preferences beforehand in the reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This results in a model capable of generating more relevant responses and rejecting inappropriate or irrelevant queries.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Some notable examples of RLHF-trained language models are OpenAI's ChatGPT (and its predecessor InstructGPT), DeepMind's Sparrow, Google's Gemini, and Anthropic's Claude.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In computer vision, RLHF has also been used to align text-to-image models.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Studies that successfully used RLHF for this goal have noted that the use of KL regularization in RLHF, which aims to prevent the learned policy from straying too far from the unaligned model, helped to stabilize the training process by reducing overfitting to the reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The final image outputs from models trained with KL regularization were noted to be of significantly higher quality than those trained without.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF was initially applied to other areas, such as the development of video game bots and tasks in simulated robotics.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, OpenAI and DeepMind trained agents to play Atari games based on human preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In classical RL-based training of such bots, the reward function is simply correlated to how well the agent is performing in the game, usually using metrics like the in-game score.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In comparison, in RLHF, a human is periodically presented with two clips of the agent's behavior in the game and must decide which one *looks* better.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This approach can teach agents to perform at a competitive level without ever having access to their score.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In fact, it was shown that RLHF can sometimes lead to superior performance over RL with score metrics because the human's preferences can contain more useful information than performance-based metrics.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The agents achieved strong performance in many of the environments tested, often surpassing human performance.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In RLHF, two different models are trained: a reward model and a reinforcement learning policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The reward model learns to determine what behavior is desirable based on human feedback, while the policy is guided by the reward model to determine the agent's actions.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Both models are commonly initialized using a pre-trained autoregressive language model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This model is then customarily trained in a supervised manner on a relatively small dataset of pairs of prompts to an assistant and their accompanying responses, written by human annotators.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The **reward model** is a function that takes a string (piece of text) as input, and produces a single number, which is the "reward".
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It is usually initialized with a pre-trained model, as this initializes it with an understanding of language and focuses training explicitly on learning human preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In addition to being used to initialize the reward model and the RL policy, the model is then also used to sample data to be compared by annotators.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The reward model is then trained by replacing the final layer of the previous model with a randomly initialized regression head.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This change shifts the model from its original classification task over its vocabulary to simply outputting a number corresponding to the score of any given prompt and response.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This model is trained on the human preference comparison data collected earlier from the supervised model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] where K is the number of responses the labelers ranked, $r_{\theta }(x,y)$ is the output of the reward model for prompt x and completion y , $y_{w}$ is the preferred completion over $y_{l}$ , $\sigma (x)$ denotes the sigmoid function, and $E[X]$ denotes the expected value.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This can be thought of as a form of logistic regression, where the model predicts the probability that a response $y_{w}$ is preferred over $y_{l}$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This loss function essentially measures the difference between the reward model's predictions and the decisions made by humans.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The goal is to make the model's guesses as close as possible to the humans' preferences by minimizing the difference measured by this equation.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In the case of only pairwise comparisons, $K=2$ , so the factor of $1/{\tbinom {K}{2}}=1$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In general, all ${\tbinom {K}{2}}$ comparisons from each prompt are used for training as a single batch.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] After training, the outputs of the model are normalized such that the reference completions have a mean score of 0.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, ${\textstyle \sum _{y}r_{\theta }(x,y)=0}$ for each query and reference pair $(x,y)$ by calculating the mean reward across the training dataset and setting it as the bias in the reward head.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The **policy model** is a function that takes a string as input, and produces another string.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Usually in language modeling, the output string is not produced in one forward pass, but by multiple forward passes, generated autoregressively.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Similarly to the reward model, the human feedback policy is also initialized from a pre-trained model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The key is to understand language generation as if it is a game to be learned by RL.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In RL, a policy is a function that maps a game state to a game action.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In RLHF, the "game" is the game of replying to prompts.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A prompt and all previously generated tokens are the game state, and generating a new token is a game action.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The first step in its training is supervised fine-tuning (SFT).
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This step does not require the reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Instead, the pre-trained model is trained on a dataset $D_{SFT}$ that contains prompt-response pairs $(x,y)$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Then, during SFT, the model is trained to auto-regressively generate the corresponding response y when given a random prompt x .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The original paper recommends to SFT for only one epoch, since more than that causes overfitting.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The dataset $D_{SFT}$ is usually written by human contractors, who write both the prompts and responses.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The second step uses a policy gradient method to the reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It uses a dataset $D_{RL}$ , which contains prompts, but not responses.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Note that $(x,y)\sim D_{\pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}}$ is equivalent to $x\sim D_{RL},y\sim \pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}(\cdot |x)$ , which means "sample a prompt from $D_{RL}$ , then sample a response from the policy".
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The first part is simply the expected reward $E[r]$ , and is standard for any RL algorithm.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The second part is a "penalty term" involving the KL divergence.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The strength of the penalty term is determined by the hyperparameter $\beta$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This KL term works by penalizing the KL divergence (a measure of statistical distance between distributions) between the model being fine-tuned and the initial supervised model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] By choosing an appropriate $\beta$ , the training can balance learning from new data while retaining useful information from the initial model, increasing generalization by avoiding fitting too closely to the new data.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Aside from preventing the new model from producing outputs too dissimilar those of the initial model, a second motivation of including the KL term is to encourage the model to output high-entropy text, so as to prevent the model from collapsing to a small number of canned responses.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In simpler terms, the objective function calculates how well the policy's responses are expected to align with human feedback.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The policy generates responses to prompts, and each response is evaluated both on how well it matches human preferences (as measured by the reward model) and how similar it is to responses the model would naturally generate.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The goal is to balance improving alignment with human preferences while ensuring the model's responses remain diverse and not too far removed from what it has learned during its initial training.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This helps the model not only to provide answers that people find useful or agreeable but also to maintain a broad understanding and avoid overly narrow or repetitive responses.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The policy function is usually trained by proximal policy optimization (PPO) algorithm.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, the parameter $\phi$ is trained by gradient ascent on the clipped surrogate function.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The value estimator is used only during training, and not outside of training.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, the advantage is computed as the difference between the reward (the expected return) and the value estimation (the expected return from the policy).
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This is used to train the policy by gradient *ascent* on it, usually using a standard momentum-gradient optimizer, like the Adam optimizer.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The original paper initialized the value estimator from the trained reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Other methods than squared TD-error might be used.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] See the actor-critic algorithm page for details.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A third term is commonly added to the objective function to prevent the model from catastrophic forgetting.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, if the model is only trained in customer service, then it might forget general knowledge in geography.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] To prevent this, the RLHF process incorporates the original language modeling objective.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] That is, some random texts x are sampled from the original pretraining dataset $D_{\text{pretrain}}$ , and the model is trained to maximize the log-likelihood of the text $\log(\pi _{\phi }^{RL}(x))$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] where $\gamma$ controls the strength of this pretraining term.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This combined objective function is called PPO-ptx, where "ptx" means "Mixing Pretraining Gradients".
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It was first used in the InstructGPT paper.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In total, this objective function defines the method for adjusting the RL policy, blending the aim of aligning with human feedback and maintaining the model's original language understanding.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] RLHF suffers from challenges with collecting human feedback, learning a reward model, and optimizing the policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Compared to data collection for techniques like unsupervised or self-supervised learning, collecting data for RLHF is less scalable and more expensive.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Its quality and consistency may vary depending on the task, interface, and the preferences and biases of individual humans.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] The effectiveness of RLHF depends on the quality of human feedback.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For instance, the model may become biased, favoring certain groups over others, if the feedback lacks impartiality, is inconsistent, or is incorrect.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] There is a risk of overfitting, where the model memorizes specific feedback examples instead of learning to generalize.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For instance, feedback predominantly from a specific demographic might lead the model to learn peculiarities or noise, along with the intended alignment.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Excessive alignment to the specific feedback it received (that is, to the bias therein) can lead to the model performing sub-optimally in new contexts or when used by different groups.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] A single reward function cannot always represent the opinions of diverse groups of people.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Even with a representative sample, conflicting views and preferences may result in the reward model favoring the majority's opinion, potentially disadvantaging underrepresented groups.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In some cases, as is possible in regular reinforcement learning, there may be a risk of the model learning to manipulate the feedback process or game the system to achieve higher rewards rather than genuinely improving its performance.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] In the case of RLHF, a model may learn to exploit the fact that it is rewarded for what is evaluated positively and not necessarily for what is actually good, which can lead to it learning to persuade and manipulate.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] For example, models might learn that apparent confidence, even if inaccurate, garners higher rewards.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Such behavior, if unchecked, is not just incentivized but can cause significant deployment issues due to the model's potential to mislead.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Studies have found that humans are not skilled at identifying mistakes in LLM outputs in complex tasks; therefore, models learning to generate confident-sounding yet incorrect text can lead to significant issues when deployed.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Similarly to RLHF, *reinforcement learning from AI feedback* (RLAIF) relies on training a preference model, except that the feedback is automatically generated.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This is notably used in Anthropic's constitutional AI, where the AI feedback is based on the conformance to the principles of a constitution.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Direct alignment algorithms (DAA) have been proposed as a new class of algorithms that seek to directly optimize large language models (LLMs) on human feedback data in a supervised manner instead of the traditional policy-gradient methods.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] These algorithms aim to align models with human intent more transparently by removing the intermediate step of training a separate reward model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Instead of first predicting human preferences and then optimizing against those predictions, direct alignment methods train models end-to-end on human-labeled or curated outputs.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This reduces potential misalignment risks introduced by proxy objectives or reward hacking.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] By directly optimizing for the behavior preferred by humans, these approaches often enable tighter alignment with human values, improved interpretability, and simpler training pipelines compared to RLHF.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Direct preference optimization (DPO) is a technique to learn human preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Like RLHF, it has been applied to align pre-trained large language models using human-generated preference data.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Unlike RLHF, however, which first trains a separate intermediate model to understand what good outcomes look like and then teaches the main model how to achieve those outcomes, DPO simplifies the process by directly adjusting the main model according to people's preferences.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It uses a change of variables to define the "preference loss" directly as a function of the policy and uses this loss to fine-tune the model, helping it understand and prioritize human preferences without needing a separate step.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Essentially, this approach directly shapes the model's decisions based on positive or negative human feedback.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] However, instead of doing the intermediate step of the reward model, DPO directly optimizes for the final policy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Usually, DPO is used for modeling human preference in pairwise comparisons, so that $N=2$ .
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] DPO eliminates the need for a separate reward model or reinforcement learning loop, treating alignment as a supervised learning problem over preference data.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] This is simpler to implement and train than RLHF and has been shown to produce comparable and sometimes superior results.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Nevertheless, RLHF has also been shown to beat DPO on some datasets, for example, on benchmarks that attempt to measure truthfulness.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Therefore, the choice of method may vary depending on the features of the human preference data and the nature of the task.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Identity preference optimization (IPO) is a modification to the original DPO objective that introduces a regularization term to reduce the chance of overfitting even when preference data is noisy.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] IPO can control the gap between the log-likelihood ratios of the policy model and the reference by always regularizing the solution towards the reference model.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] It allows learning directly from preferences without a reward modelling stage and without relying on the Bradley-Terry modelling assumption that assumes that pairwise preferences can be substituted with pointwise rewards.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Kahneman-Tversky optimization (KTO) is another direct alignment algorithm drawing from prospect theory to model uncertainty in human decisions.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Unlike DPO, KTO requires only a binary feedback signal (desirable or undesirable) instead of explicit preference pairs.
[src:ppo-algorithm/reinforcement-learning-from-human-feedback] Since many real-world feedback pipelines yield "like/dislike" data more easily than pairwise comparisons, KTO is designed to be data-efficient and to reflect "loss aversion" more directly by using a straightforward notion of "good vs. bad" at the example level.
